    <h2 class="title mt-4">Orbital</h2>

    Vodafone Qualitics Grading: 9.8 / 10.0
    <p>
      During the mandatory internship semester of my study program I partnered
      up with Vodafone Germany. I ended up designing and implementing a
      prototype software using <strong>Raspberry Pi</strong>'s (and similar
      small-scale <strong>edge devices</strong>) which would analyze the
      infamous "last meters" an ISP does not have control over: From the street
      connection to the customer. The software would be <strong
        >fully automatic</strong
      >, the customer just has to receive the device and plug it into their
      router. Tests the device would take could be easily designed. Each
      customer would receive a <strong>specialized collection</strong> of tests to
      be run, specifically tailored to their reported problems. Enough data would
      be gathered and <strong>automatically analyzed</strong> to pinpoint issues exactly
      without troublesome technician appointments. The software could identify any
      set of common home network issues, such as insufficient bandwidth, network overload,
      spotty connections, partially broken ISP lines, routing issues, interference
      and many more. A <strong>web-interface</strong> was provided for the customer
      and ISP to easily see what is going on and what fixes are recommended. The whole
      stack was build using <strong>Rust</strong>, <strong>HTML</strong>, <strong
        >SASS</strong
      >, <strong>Figma</strong>, <strong>Visual Paradigm</strong> and <strong
        >various languages</strong
      > for the test suites.
    </p>
    Due to internship regulations I cannot publish the project publicly.

